  "prompt": "How can you delete all photos from your iPhone?",
  "response": "There are several ways to delete all photos from your iPhone, depending on what you want to achieve and where the photos are stored:\n\n**Method 1: Deleting from the Photos App (Deletes from iCloud Photo Library if enabled)**\n\nThis is the most common method and will delete photos from your iPhone and, if you use iCloud Photo Library, from all your devices synced with iCloud.\n\n1.  **Open the Photos app.**\n2.  **Go to \"Albums\".**  At the bottom of the screen, you might see a \"Library\" tab (which is newer iOS versions), or you'll see \"Albums\".  If you're in the Library tab, tap \"Albums\" at the bottom.\n3.  **Select \"All Photos\".**  Scroll down until you see the \"All Photos\" album.  This contains all your photos and videos on your phone.\n4.  **Tap \"Select\".**  In the upper-right corner of the screen, tap the \"Select\" button.\n5.  **Select All or Drag:**\n    *   **iOS 17 and later:** Tap the ellipsis (...) button in the bottom right corner and choose \"Select All\".\n    *   **Older iOS versions (without Select All):** This is a bit more cumbersome. You can tap each photo individually.  However, a faster method is to tap and hold the first photo, then drag your finger down to select a large number of photos quickly.  Continue dragging until all photos are selected.  Be aware this can be a bit laggy if you have thousands of photos.\n\n6.  **Tap the Trash Can Icon.**  At the bottom-right corner of the screen, tap the trash can icon.\n7.  **Confirm Deletion.**  A pop-up will appear asking if you want to delete the selected photos.  Tap \"Delete [Number] Photos.\"\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   **iCloud Photo Library:**  If you have iCloud Photo Library enabled (Settings > Your Name > iCloud > Photos), deleting photos from your iPhone using this method will also delete them from iCloud and all other devices connected to the same iCloud account.  These photos will move to the \"Recently Deleted\" album.\n*   **Recently Deleted:**  Deleted photos go to the \"Recently Deleted\" album in the Photos app. They will stay there for 30 days, after which they are permanently deleted.  You can manually delete them permanently from the \"Recently Deleted\" album if you want to free up space immediately. To do this:\n    *   Go to the \"Albums\" tab in the Photos app.\n    *   Scroll down to \"Utilities\" and tap \"Recently Deleted\".\n    *   Tap \"Select\" in the upper-right corner.\n    *   Tap \"Delete All\" in the lower-left corner.\n    *   Confirm the deletion.\n\n**Method 2: Disabling iCloud Photo Library and then Deleting (Preserves iCloud Copies)**\n\nThis method allows you to remove photos from your iPhone *without* deleting them from your iCloud account.  **This is crucial if you want to keep your photos backed up to iCloud but want them gone from your iPhone.**\n\n1.  **Disable iCloud Photo Library:**\n    *   Go to **Settings > Your Name > iCloud > Photos.**\n    *   Toggle **iCloud Photos** to the **off** position.\n    *   When prompted, choose **\"Remove from iPhone\"**  This is the key step!  Choosing \"Download and Keep Originals\" will do the opposite of what you want.\n2.  **Wait for Photos to Remove:**  Allow some time for the photos to be removed from your iPhone. This can take a while depending on the number of photos and your internet connection.  Your iPhone might show \"Optimizing Storage\" or something similar during this process.\n3.  **Delete Remaining Photos (if any):** Once the iCloud Photo Library is disabled and the initial removal is complete, check the Photos app.  If there are any photos remaining, follow the steps in Method 1 to select and delete them.\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   **Backup First:**  Before disabling iCloud Photo Library, double-check that all your photos are indeed backed up to iCloud. You can verify this by logging into iCloud.com on a computer and checking your Photos library there.\n*   **iCloud Storage:**  Disabling iCloud Photo Library will mean your iPhone will no longer automatically back up new photos to iCloud. Make sure you have other backup methods in place if you want to continue backing up your photos.\n\n**Method 3:  Factory Reset (Erases EVERYTHING on the iPhone - Use with extreme caution!)**\n\nThis is a drastic measure that will erase *everything* on your iPhone, including all photos, apps, contacts, and settings.  **Only use this as a last resort** if you're selling or giving away your phone, or if you're having serious software issues.  **MAKE SURE YOU HAVE A BACKUP OF ANYTHING YOU WANT TO KEEP BEFORE DOING THIS!**\n\n1.  **Back Up Your iPhone:**  **ESSENTIAL!**  Go to Settings > Your Name > iCloud > iCloud Backup and tap \"Back Up Now.\" Or, back up to your computer using iTunes (or Finder on macOS Catalina and later).\n2.  **Turn off Find My iPhone:** Go to Settings > Your Name > Find My and turn off \"Find My iPhone.\" You'll need your Apple ID password to do this.\n3.  **Erase All Content and Settings:**\n    *   Go to **Settings > General > Transfer or Reset iPhone.**\n    *   Tap **Erase All Content and Settings.**\n    *   Follow the on-screen instructions to confirm. You'll likely need to enter your passcode and Apple ID password.\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   **Irreversible:**  A factory reset is permanent. Once you start the process, there's no turning back.\n*   **Backup is Crucial:**  If you don't back up your iPhone, you will lose all your data.\n\n**Choosing the Right Method:**\n\n*   **Want to delete photos from your iPhone and iCloud (and all synced devices):**  Use **Method 1**.\n*   **Want to delete photos from your iPhone but keep them in iCloud:**  Use **Method 2**.\n*   **Want to completely erase your iPhone (selling/giving away):**  Use **Method 3** (after backing up important data).\n\n**Before you delete anything, always double-check that you have a backup of any photos or videos you want to keep.** There's nothing worse than accidentally deleting precious memories!\n",
